* version bump to 0.2.0 * added bunch of new nesting functionality * added input/output accessors instead of binding to stdin/stdout * added _ for last result * changed command format (no more sigils)
cleaned up code (ugly comments)
* added new commands: help, status * removed exit_at alias for jump_to, now only jump_to is valid * updated documentation * added another format for pry method, can now use 5.pry or pry(5)

formatting

added ls/cd/cd..
nested pry, seems to create an anonymous object e.g pry (wait for new repl) then pry -- self changes!. Also exit_program seems broken!
Ripper for 1.9, RubyParser for 1.8. Fixed 1.8 inspect difficulties, added help for new commands, using method_source gem, updated README
updated docs
Version to 0.2.8; moved default_prompt and wait_prompt to Pry class. Instance prompts default to these values (can override by calling default_prompt/wait_prompt accessors on instance
added default of TOPLEVEL_BINDING to Pry.start()
version bump 0.3.0, added method_doc and friends, added cat, updated README, adjusted Rakefile to use 0.2.0 method_source gem

Added out parameter to Output class, so can redirect standard output to any valid IO object. Renamed show_instance_method to show_imethod and method_doc to show_doc, and instance_method_doc to show_idoc, updated README.
fixed docs
fixed readme

* added tests (test.rb and test_helper.rb files) * defined input/output accessors for Pry class to set global defaults for input and output (overridable by specific instances). * Added reset_defaults method to set input/output and prompt lambdas back to defaults * added output callback for 'cd' command * changed eval_string += val to eval_string << val in Pry#r method, for performance reasons (no copy made with <<)
all tests passing, new functionality in form of: hash args to Pry.start() for :input and :output

passing all tests. created a __binding__ method to return a binding unpolluted by Pry context, no longer using instance_eval, thanks to Mon_Ouie's trick. Added test for multi-line, added nest for class nesting
passing ALL tests now for 1.8 AND 1.9
commands now separated and pluggable as a hash, defined in commands.rb
Save before major refactor to split up Pry into pry_class and pry_instance
split Pry into 3 more files: pry_class (for class methods) pry_instance (instance methods) and core_extensions, for extensions to Object (e.g pry and __binding__ methods)
slight refactor, just code aesthetics and formatting

removed ability of Object#pry to pass options parameters, as too confusing when invoked in this form: obj.pry(:input => Input.new)  i.e opens pry session on {:input => .. } rather than redirects input for pry session
bringing most of output functionality into commands, since 99% of output is command output

* completely merged Output and Commands classes, reduced Output to just a simple puts() method, a la Input and read() * Commands now completely manages 'help', so that 'help' returns full command list/doco and 'help cmd' returns doc for just that command * Turned out.session_start() and out.session_end() into hook methods: Pry.hooks :before_session, and :after_session * Refactored Pry#initialize, so no longer individually setting accessors and hash options, instead using ConfigOptions to iterate over accessors and set their default value to Pry.send(accessor_name) * TO DO: rewrite tests in terms of new program structure, since they're all failing due to major change (not because functionality is lacking but due to assumptions tests were making about program structure)
minor changes: added Pry instance (__pry__) to status, changed _pry_ to __pry__, minor aesthetic changes..decreased ljust() for help, changed cd .. match in command_info to regex
combined default_prompt and wait_prompt into one prompt array called default_prompt; added ls_methods and ls_imethods commands, version bump to 0.4.0
start at docs
added .yardopts
updated docs
changed @options to @options
now clearing :val rather than :eval_string in commands so that current expression context is not destroyed when running pry command. Also added !pry command to enter a pry session
updating tests to reflect new program organization/design
other tests passing: commands
adding back a bunch of tests, almost finished. Also renamed default_prompt to prompt and prompt to get_prompt, etc
changed get_prompt to select_prompt
moved input select logic to Pry#readline; updated tests to reflect that Pry.input and Pry.output now accept duck-typed IOs
added completion (taken from irb). Remember to remove hardcoding expecation of command_info from Pry#re() method, need to turn command addition into DSL
implementing command dsl
got CommandBase working; just need to migrate old commands into a new commands.rb and move CommandBase into command_base.rb
saving before refactor to implement action block instead of action proc for commands. All tests passing in 1.8 and 1.9.
starting to write the behemoth that is README.markdown
added Pry.sessions and Pry#parent, for more info on pry sessions. Also completed more documentation
FInished documenting all customizable options in README.markdown; just cleanup and clarification and example programs left before 0.4.0 release
oops, fixed bug in prompts.rb where was using nest instead of nest_level
finished updating and improving command API; now command API is as follows: command 'blah' do |x| puts x; end   where x is a parameter passed to the command from the pry prompt
Regex working
updated README to reflect major new changes to Pry::CommandBase class
updated README, fixed a few typos and badly named sections
made ls_methods and ls_imethods commands now show all public/private/protected methods - not just public
more docs for hooks, print, and prompts
removed input.rb and output.rb
fixed arity problems with action.call in process_commands; where 1.8.7 was complaining if wrong number of args were passed (but 1.9.2 didnt care); now passing along correct number of args
made it so aliases are now added as separate commands, no longer an array of commands - makes it easier to override aliased commands in subclasses

added import_from, delete, run to command API. Also added examples, added more tests, and changed the way that commands work using split instead of regex captures. Also added output and trget methods to Pry::CommandBase
updating docs, and added --private flag to .yardopts to include private methods in documentation
another doc update, documented completion.rb and reworded some sections in README
almost ready for 0.4.0 release, created new example_input2.rb example for advanced input usage

Updated more docs and formatting.Changed tests to remove opts[:output] and then removed opts[:output]; replaced with output method, changed prompt in example_commands.rb to have a math* wait prompt. Added bullet points to examples in README.markdown. Added more info on TexPlay and Gosu for example_image_editn
added ls_methods and ls_imethods doc. to README

Version 0.4.0 release.Bunch of new changes including: tab completion, major customizability (ability to read from and write to any object that supported #readline and #puts respectively), extensive tests, command API, examples, lots of documentation and more.n
separated customization documentation from main README
added wiki/ as nested git repo, removed command_info as attr_accessor from command_base
added .document to bring in wiki/ files, and using a yard file link in README.markdown to link to the wiki files
fixed customizing pry link for README
reworded some sections in README and Customizing-pry.md to make configurability options clearer

Made it so defining methods on a pry'd on object puts the methods on the singleton class of the object rather than on the class. Added rubygems-test support.Alternatively, if the object cannot support singleton methods, e.g immediates and Numerics, the method will go on the class instead.n

Version 0.4.1* Made is to 'def meth;end' in an object (not a class) defines singleton methods, not methods on the class.n* Reorganized and reworded some documentation, adding info on rubygems-testn* added rubygems-test supportn* added more tests to reflect new method definition behaviourn
added new 'alias_command' and 'desc' commands to CommandBase; also made it so show_method comamnd without parameters does a show_method on __method__

Version 0.4.2* Added alias_command and desc commands to Pry::CommandBasen* Added pry and version tasks to Rakefile to start a pry session and show current versionn* Added tests for alias_command and desc commandsn* made it so ls_methods and ls_imethods return sort arraysn* made it so show_method without a paramater displays current method, if exists, who displays error if notn

0.4.8, re-release due to rubygems problems. Also, removed show_version task from Rakefile, and replaced it with a version task
Version 0.4.9pre1. Added show_command, added -g option to ls and got it working in combination with -c, e.g ls -gc. Changed documentation for !

Major change, clipping receiver object representation to #<> notation if #inspect returns a string of size > 60 chars. This should make it more workable when prying on enormous objects. Other changes: shellwords, new commands, some command modifications etc* Now using Shellwords to split input string into args to pass to action procn* added version command, to show pry versionn* added Pry.view_clip(), clips large #inspect to #<> notationn* added inspect alias for catn* added current method info to status commandn* added ruby/pry version info to status commandn

Got rid of show_imethod and show_idoc, merged into show-method and show-doc with special -M option. Changed all underscored command names to hyphenated-names, e.g jump-to instead of jump_to.* added a bunch of new command options to ls command, supercharging it. Using optparse.n* added options to show-method and show-docn* now showing file/line for show-method, show-doc, show-command commandsn* cleaned up 'help', and got rid of aliases from help display; now showing aliases in primary command help output.n
version 0.5.0pre4 Almost ready for release. Updated examples to match new changes, updated README.
added private/public/protected flags for ls method display

* version 0.5.0 release* Use clipped version of Pry.view() for large objectsn* Exit Pry session on ^dn* Use Shellwords for breaking up parameters to pry commandsn* Use OptionParser to parse options for default pry commandsn* Add version commandn* Refactor 'status' command: add current method infon* Add meth_name_from_binding utility lambda to commands.rbn* Add -M, -m, -v(erbose), -a(ll), -s(uper), -l(ocals), -i(ivars), -k(klassntvars), etc options to lsn* add -M(instance method) options to show-method and show-docn* add --help option to most commandsn* Get rid of ls_method and ls_imethods (subsumed by more powerful ls)n* Get rid of show_idoc and show_imethodn* Add special eval-file command that evals target file in current contextn
version 0.5.1, fixed some documentation related bugs and improved clarity
version 0.5.2: corrected ^d behaviour; now performs a throw(:breakout) rather than relying on existence of 'quit' command.

version 0.6.8, added whereami command, made .pryrc run at the start of each runtime session, put syntax highlighting on by default

version 0.6.8.1 - fixed rubinius raising when command line pry was invoked* added :__script__ test to hooks toon* raise was due to top-level rubinius __method__ returning :__script__n  and not simply returning nil (like MRI/JRUBY)n* Fix was to include :__script__ in the test.n* also slightly improved working in README.markdownn

Starting to integrate YARD support. Currently support 'doc' command which retrieves docs of ruby-core for both methods and instance methods

got pry working with pry-doc, and modified show-doc and show-method commands to use pry-doc if pry-doc exists, otherwise to use source_location based techniques.
added process/parsing of comments

version 0.7.0, added pry-doc support and a few misc things.* added pry-doc support for ruby core C methods, (show-doc andn  show-method)n* added _ex_ local for recovering last exceptionn* added -mj option to ls to display methods defined strictly onn  singleton class.n
version 0.7.1, added better error checking for non-existent C source

version 0.7.1, upgraded dependency on method_source to 0.4.0 so that accurately returns C source for immediate value instance methods.* refactored repl into 2 help methods: repl_prologue, repl_epiloguen* added session_target method to Pry instances so can retrieve targetnof session for parents, e.g _pry_.parent.session_targetn* refactored ls command to use Symbol#to_procn

updated README slightly
version 0.7.7, added improved yard parser for show-doc command. Major refactor/code cleanup in pry_instance.rb

version 0.7.7.2, fixed jruby support and improved `cd` command so it can operate on arbitrary expressions
added BasicObject support (class not instances).And support inspecting objects without to_s and inspect by defaultingnto 'unknown'. Also slightly refactored tests, moved more stuff into test_helper.n

added execution of shell commands when ':' is first char of command, forwards to system(). Added back in #{direc} before requires as without it the installed gems were interferring
version 0.8.0pre2, refactored out command_processor.rb. fixed '?' as alias for show-doc (needed to escape regex).
version 0.8.0pre3, removed system(cmd) for  system command
added more documentation, proper error message for failed .cd command, added -t option to cat-file command

version 0.8.0pre4, suppress output from command that dont have return values. suppress output from all expressions that end in a ';'. Added `gem-cd` command that chdir to the directory containing the gem files.

turned chomp! into an rstrip! in process_line(). Fixed 1.8.7 compat for `read_between_lines` function commands.rb. Removed before/after hook output text (too spammy). Fixed file-mode completion, so it works straight away. CHanged 'pry' rake task to 'binding.pry' instead of just 'pry' so that context is given.

fixed `run` command builder, now takes target parameter, also accepts system commands.Also:n* changed Rakefile to remove the -k flag from bacon testn* changed pry_instance attr_reader to attr_accessor in CommandProcessor classn* updated tests to reflect new `run` parametersn
* got run command working by passing in extra 'target' argument. Got   command string interpolation working, so .cd #{my_dir} now works.

version 0.8.0pre5, Added special _file_ and _dir_ locals that are created when file-based commands are run (e.g show-method, show-command, show-doc, whereami, cat-file, etc) Can then be used like: `.cd #{_dir_}`. Fixed string interpolation so it's 1.8 compatible.
added 'reset' command (exec(pry)) to bin/pry executable
Added pager and pagebreaks (-b option) to show-method, show-doc, cat-file. Also changed output headers to get rid of --, as per epitron's commit.
Added pagebreaks (-b option) to show-command. Fixed some edgecase behaviour of the -b option. Slightly refactored commands.rb
refactored code in `help` command command_base.rb
refactored commands.rb, converting lambdas to methods and putting into command_helpers.rb.Also changed run_command in pry_class.rb to use #dup instead of #clone, but innYARV? (worked fine in MRI)n
fixed suppression of exceptions by ';'
changed Pry.run_command so it works on both rbx (using Object#clone) and YARV 1.9 (using Object#dup).Both implementations have bugs.n
passed parameter to whereami to stop 1.8 warning about lacking arguments (need to fix this properly in 0.9.0 in Pry.run_command at some point)

Now using lesspipe by default for paging long text output on unix. Use -f to turn off (flood option)* Still using simpler_pager on windowsn* made all CommandHelper methods privaten* fixed negative line numbers bugn
verson 0.8.0pre7, added number of lines to all headers (make_header in command_helpers.rb)
converted stagger_output() to always use lesspipe unless exception is raised; when exception to use simple_pager. This should ensure windows uers who have `less` can use it.
refactored commands_helper.rb and commands.rb slightly. Renamed file-mode command to `shell-mode`.

added gist-method & ri commands. Aliased $ to show-method* fixed _dir_ bug (was just equal to _file_)n* Major refactor of show-doc and show-method commandsn* making start on optional/installable commandsn

Added 'install' command and stub commands, allowing user to install commands that have dependencies on gems after pry has already been installed.* The `install` command manages the installation of the gem, refreshingnof the gem cache. The command itself though must 'require' the gem.n* Also refactored a bunch of helper methods on command_base.rb into ancommand_base_helpers.rb file and CommandBaseHelpers module.n
fixed some bugs in `gist-method` command and gave it a dependency on 'gist' gem. Added `.<shell command>` descriptive command (cannot be executed). Fixed tests.
experimenting with bold colors

added new `stat` command to read basic show basic method information. Refactored command_helpers.rb and command_base_helpers.rb, moving some methods up into command_base_helpers. `ls` command now uses a pager. Some headings made 'bold'
Added comments to command_processor.rb, added bold text to output from `stat` command.

Add prompt stack to fix bug where prompt is not restored after returning from shell-modeWhen returning from shell-mode, the prompt is not properly restored.nThe problem is that it gets clobbered by the new prompt, so we need somewhere to store it.nThis adds a prompt stack so you can push and pop prompts in order to temporarily changenthe current prompt and then later restore the previous prompt.nnprompt and prompt= are also overridden to have meaning in the context of the prompt stack.n

This closes issue #241. Files are not eval'd at top-level and temps are inserted into the input buffer (eval_string). edit --ex now auto-reloads too.Auto-reloads can be suppressed using the new `-n` option. Situation is now the following:nn(1) files are not reloaded by defaultn(2) if files are reloaded (using -r) they are eval'd at topleveln(3) edit --ex is reloaded by default and is eval'd at toplevel (same as files)n(4) edit -t or just `edit` is reloaded by default and is inserted into input buffer (eval_string)n(5) if you need to suppress auto-reloading for edit --ex or edit -t then also pass the -n switchn

Pry now indents code similar to IRB.Code is indented using the class Pry::Indent. This class uses an internal stacknthat contains the indentation levels for each line of code. Certain keywordsnsuch as class or def will add data to this stack so that the next line isnindented, other keywords such as end or } will remove data from the stack,ncausing the next line to be un-indented.nnPry::Indent is hooked into Pry#retrieve_line as well as Pry#readline. This meansnthat both input strings as well as the ones displayed by show-method arenindented. Sadly due to the way Readline works input strings are indented similarnto IRB. This means that instead of the following:nn> class Usern>   def initializen>   endn> endnnYou'll get the following:nn> class Usern>   def initializen> endn>   endnnWhile annoying there doesn't seem to be a way to work around this issue. Luckilynthe show-method command indents your code properly.nnBy default indentation is turned on. This can be turned off (or back on) usingnthe configuration item Pry.config.indent. However, if you turn this option offnafter a method is defined show-method will still show it with indentation asnindentation happens on input rather than only when code is displayed.nnFor more information see Pry::Indent#indent in lib/pry/indent.rb.nnSigned-off-by: Yorick Peterse <yorickpeterse@gmail.com>n
Compatibility with 1.8 and friends.Signed-off-by: Yorick Peterse <yorickpeterse@gmail.com>

Reset written lines using tput.When writing code in Pry blocks of code are now aligned properly thanks to n`tput`. This was inspired by https://github.com/janlelis/ripl-auto_indent/blob/master/lib/ripl/auto_indent.rb#L53-62. Please note that currently show-method is broken as itnwill also trigger the line resetting.nnSigned-off-by: Yorick Peterse <yorickpeterse@gmail.com>n

Pry::Indent now handles single line statements.Previously certain lines of code would break the indentation process. Fornexample, the following code would result in incorrect indentation:nndef hello; endnputs Hello worldnnThis would result in the following:nndef hello; endn  puts Hello worldnnI've worked around this issue by adding a new methodn(Pry::Indent#skip_indentation?) that does a lookahead on the list of tokens tondetermine if a line should be indented or not. It's probably not the mostnefficient way of doing it but it makes it quite easy to add more tokens to thenlist without adding a lot more complexity.nnSigned-off-by: Yorick Peterse <yorickpeterse@gmail.com>n

Allow use of hash-based hooks, but show warning.* Shows a deprecation warning when used with a link to the new `Pry::Hooks` documentation.n* When hash-based hooks are used they create anonymous hooks for the associated event.ni.e Pry.hooks = { :before_session => proc { puts 'hi' } }, the 'name' of that hook is `nil`.n* Anonymous hooks (nil-named) are different to ordinary hooks in that they dont raise an exception when user attempts to define another of the same name, they just silently overwrite previous one. This is tonmimic the old hash-based behaviour.n* Pry::Hooks[] and Pry::Hooks[]= are defined too, and they get and set the anonymous hook for the given event, i.e hooks[:before_session] = proc { hi } is equivalent to: hook.add_hook(:before_session, nil,nproc { hi })n* Proc::Hook#[] and Pry::Hooks#[]= also display deprecation warnings.n

Set Pry::Slop equal to Slop (v2.4.4)We've decided not to upgrade our slop dependency to version 3 fornseveral reasons:nn1. People who are currently using pry in their programs are using slopnversion 2; and they may not realise this. Bumping the slop dependencyncould therefore break people's code in subtle ways. By removing thendependency completely we make it obvious that breakage has occurred, andnallows programs to chose their own version of slop.nn2. The new version of slop is incompatible with pry. As a command-linentool we use our option parsing library very very intensely; and as suchnwe've grown used to (and even embraced) it's warts, inconcistencies andnundocumented behaviours. Upgrading the slop dependency at this pointnrequires a lot of fix up work both on the slop codebase and the pryncodebase.nn3. The slop API is implicitly part of the pry API for defining customncommands; by changing that API we run a significant risk of breakingnpeople's pry extensions.nn4. The problems in 1., 2. and 3. are going to recur every time slop releasesna new version.nn5. Doing this does not preclude upgrading the version of slop we use innthe future. Beacuse 1. will not occur anymore, the only breakage that wencan cause is in pry extensions; this seems resonable providing we signalnthe fact that we're doing it (for example by updating the majornversion number).n

Provide a place for commands to store state.Commands can store state on an  `OpenStruct` exposed via the `state` method.nThis `OpenStruct` is guaranteed to be unique to the command and to the associated Pry instance.nne.gnncreate_command my-test don  def processnstate.my_state ||= 0nstate.my_state += 1n  endnendnnThe above `state.my_state` variable will increment by one for each invocation of `my-test`.nFurther, it will not intefere with any state on `my-test` for any other Pry instance or withnany `state.my_state` variables defined for other commands on the same Pry instance.n

Enormously important fix

Escape user input before completing it.User input should be escaped using Regexp.escape() before trying to figure outnwhat data to use for the Readline completion system. Not escaping this inputnwould cause Pry to fail for input such as `[10, 20].map(&:class)`.nnThis problem was caused due to lib/completion.rb converting the input (in thisncase it would be :class)) to a Regexp object. Because this, when converted tona Regexp object, is invalid it would cause Pry to throw a RegexpError error andnbail out.nnSee #601 for more information.nnSigned-off-by: Yorick Peterse <yorickpeterse@gmail.com>n

Completion for instance and class variables.Pry is now able to complete variable names for instance and class variables, asnwell as being able to complete methods and the like on these variables.nnSigned-off-by: Yorick Peterse <yorickpeterse@gmail.com>n

provide CLI 'pry my_file.rb' functionality to load file through REPL loopThis is an interesting trick as it processes your file as if itnwas user input in an interactive session. As a result, all Pryncommands are available, and they are executed non-interactively. Furthermorenthe session becomes interactive when the repl loop processes an'make-interactive' command in the file. The session also becomesninteractive when an exception is encountered, enabling you to fixnthe error before returning to non-interactive processing with then'make-non-interactive' command.n

Implement `cd -` commandThe `cd -` command allows a user to toggle between last two scopes.nnExample:nn  [1] pry(main)> cd :foon  [2] pry(:foo):1> cd :barn  [3] pry(:bar):2> cd -n   ^ save :bar and togglen  [4] pry(:foo):1> cd 44n   ^ we are back at foon  [5] pry(44):2> cd ..n  [6] pry(:foo):1> cd ..n  [7] pry(main)> cd -n   ^ save main and togglen  [8] pry(:foo):1>n   ^ we are back at foonnSigned-off-by: Kyrylo Silin <kyrylosilin@gmail.com>nSigned-off-by: Yorick Peterse <yorickpeterse@gmail.com>n

Change behavior of `cd -` commandSince banister begged me to do that... completely rewrite `cd -`ncommand (implemetation is much simpler now).nnThis commit brings such changes:nn  * completely rewrite behavior of `cd -` command;nn  * implement ScratchPad aka Pad for unit testing purposes (bynbanister);nn  * use Pad riches in the unit tests for `cd -` command;nn  * remove verbose and clunky unit tests;nnThis commit brings new meaning to the `cd -` command. The mainndifference is that the new command saves entire binding stack, not justnthe last binding. Let me show you an example of the variance betweennthese two implemetations:nn  * Old `cd -` implementation saves *only* last binding. With our nextn`cd -` invocation our interjacent results are lost:n  [1] pry(main)> cd 1/2/3/../4n  [2] pry(4):3> cd -n  [3] pry(main)> cd -n  [4] pry(4):1> nestingn  Nesting status:n  --n  0. main (Pry top level)n  1. 4nn  Also, there are a few bugs in old `cd -` command:nn* you type `cd :foo`, `cd 1/2/3` and `cd -`. The last commandn  relocates you to the scope of `3` (leaves you where you was),n  when `:foo` is expected;nn* you type `cd :foo`, `cd 1/2/3/../4`, `cd -`. The last commandn  relocates you to the scope of `3`, when `:foo` is expected.nn  * New and shiny `cd -` is devoid of those shortcomings:n  [1] pry(main)> cd 1/2/3/../4n  [2] pry(4):3> cd -n  [3] pry(main)> cd -n  [4] pry(4):3> nestingn  Nesting status:n  --n  0. main (Pry top level)n  1. 1n  2. 2n  3. 4nnAs I said before, this solution is *much* simpler and less error-prone.nnSigned-off-by: Kyrylo Silin <kyrylosilin@gmail.com>n

Initial implementation of fast show-source command.This requires an updated method_source gem. This approach works by reading all code between the start of the class definitionnand the method with the highest line number in one go. Since we know this chunk of code is valid we can avoid the expensive eval-based validity checks.nOnce we have primed the expression buffer with this chunk of code we then start the expensive checks looking for a complete expression, but there shouldn't benmany lines of code left since we've already processed the last method in the class definition. Using this technique i was able to show-source the 2000 line definition ofnActiveRecord::Base in under a second.n

Be more careful exception handling in Readline [Fixes #632, #605]Firstly wrap the entire completion_proc in a begin/rescue/end so thatneven if something we're not expecting goes wrong, we don't fail.nnSecondly, only throw the user out of pry if reading from readline failsnfive times in a row. This avoids a transient error (like a time-out, orna failed tab completion) from kicking you out of pry; but also avoidsnthe infinite looping problem that can happen if the error is not transient.n

Store `hist --replay <i>` calls in historyFix issue #484 (hist --replay N isn't stored in history).nnFirst, make some small amendments to existing code:nn  * Make helper methods of hist command private;nn  * What an irony! Amend the name of the duplicated test inn`test_input.rb` (should not contain duplicated lines test).nnSecondly, resolve the issue. There is one notable moment in currentnimplementation. Although `hist --replay` calls are being stored innhistory, you cannot replay entries of this kind (you cannot replaynanother call request to replay). Let me show an example:nn  [1] pry(main)> hist --show 46894n  46894: hist --replay 46675..46677n  [2] pry(main)> hist --show 46675..46677n  46675: 1+1n  46676: a = 100n  46677: hist --tailn  [3] pry(main)> hist --replay 46894n  Error: Replay index 46894 points out to another replay call: `hist -r 46675..46677`n  [4] pry(main)>nnThere are two reasons for that.nnReason one or my incompetencen-----------------------------nnFirst of all, I simply failed to implement such behaviour. With currentnstate of things (that are introduced in this commit), if you do notnraise `Pry::CommandError`, you cannot guarantee that only user's inputnis getting stored in history. Here's an example when we get unwantednentry in history:nn  [1] pry(main)> hist --show 46894n  46894: hist --replay 46675..46677n  [2] pry(main)> hist --show 46675..46677n  46675: 1+1n  46676: a = 100n  46677: hist --tail 4n  [3] pry(main)> hist --replay 46894n  => 2n  => 100n  47021: hist --show 46894n  47022: hist --show 46675..46677n  47023: hist --replay 46894n  47024: hist --replay 46675..46677n  [8] pry(main)>nnNote that a user typed only `hist --replay 46894`. But the last savednentry in history is the entry to which user's input, actually, pointednout (`hist --replay 46675..46677`). So if you press up-arrow key, younwill get not what you expected.nnReason two or Whoa, whoa, boy! There is a real reasonn-------------------------------------------------------nnBut the main reason is that you can fall into a loop trap, when bothnhist --replay calls point to each other. Example of a loop trap:nn  [31] pry(main)> hist --tail 4n  47027: hist --tailn  47028: hist --replay 47028n  47029: hist --tailn  47030: hist --replay 47032n  [32] pry(main)> hist -r 47030n  # We've just fallen into a loop trap. Let's break out of it.n  ^Cn  [416] pry(main)> hist --tail 5n  47409: hist --replay 47032n  47410: hist --replay 47030n  47411: hist --replay 47032n  47412: hist --replay 47030n  47413: hist --replay 47032n  [417] pry(main)>nnNote the number of current line (417).nnFinally, add some unit tests for this commit.nnSigned-off-by: Kyrylo Silin <kyrylosilin@gmail.com>n

Extend ClassCommand so it can define sub commandsCreate `ClassCommand::Options` class, which ties up sub commands andndefault options together.nnLet's consider the command `food make --tea`. `food` is a command,n`make` is a sub command and `--tea` is an option of `make` sub command.nWe can access `--tea` via `opts[:make][:tea].nnAlso, we can check the freshness of our food like so: `food --freshness`.n`--freshness` is a default option. We can access it like so:n`opts.freshness?` or `opts[:freshness]`.nnAdd unit tests for `ClassCommand::Option` and some other tests thatnreflect the additions.nnFinally, document everything and fix different typos in the existingndocumentation.nnSigned-off-by: Kyrylo Silin <kyrylosilin@gmail.com>n

Assign default value to `:listing` optionWhen you create a class command, there is a problem with `:listing`noption, which doesn't carry the correct default value. Consider thenexample:nn  class MakeMeHappy < Pry::ClassCommandnmatch 'woot'n  endnn`MakeMeHappy` command matches against 'woot' String, but its `:listing`noption is set to the nil String, which is incorrect. We can fix it bynsetting `:listing` explicitly:nn  command_options :listing => 'woot'nnIt's a repetitive task, so we can automate it. Holy smoke, this why wenall use computers, after all!nnWith help of this commit there is no need to set `:listing` manually.nPry will handle it for you.nnSigned-off-by: Kyrylo Silin <kyrylosilin@gmail.com>n

Fix Pry.run_commandThe problem was that Pry#rep() no longer works on its own, it'snnecessary to use Pry#repl() instead. This is because many new API, likenPry::CodeObject.lookup now get the target binding directly from the _pry_ instancen(Pry#current_context), rather than requiring it to be passed innseparately. This saves us a parameter.nnThe reason Pry#rep doesnt work with Pry::CodeObject.lookup (and sonshow-source/show-doc etc) is that the binding_stack is only set up innPry#repl_prologue, and it is the binding_stack (via Pry#current_context)nthat is accessed by Pry::CodeObject and pals.n

add Pry::CommandSet#[]=.Pry::CommandSet#[]= can be used to re-assign commands or add new ones tona command set. The key matches the pattern of a command you'd like tonreplace and the value is the command you'd the pattern to be matchednwith.nnThe key is really important. You could say this:nnPry.commands.command hello don  output.puts Hello! :)nendnPry.commands[help] = Pry.commands[hello]nnI would expect help to print Hello! :), but the command is bound tonthe pattern hello. A new copy of the hello command is creatednand the key is used as the match pattern, so help will print Hello! :).nnYou can use #[]= to replace commands, maybe your own 'help' implementation:nPry.commands[help] = MyHelpCommandnnCommands can also be deleted by assigning a value of nil:nPry.commands[help] = nilnnI decided to implement this based on SO post found here:nhttp://stackoverflow.com/questions/17475829/configure-help-output-in-pryn

implement Pry global and pry-local configuration.maybe best explained with an example:n  [1] pry(main)> Pry.config.hi = hin  => hin  [2] pry(main)> _pry_.config.hin  => hin  [3] pry(main)> _pry_.config.x = 1n  => 1n  [4] pry(main)> Pry.config.xn  => niln  [5] pry(main)>nn'Pry.config' is an instance of Pry::Config::Default. it defines the initialndefault configuration values an instance of 'Pry' is going to have. an instancenof 'Pry' uses an instance of Pry::Config who relies on Pry.config as a defaultnor fallback for keys it cannot find locally.nnfor example 'Pry.config.color = true' is seen by _all_ pry REPLs who are activenbut _pry_.config.color = false is seen only by the REPL session being interactednwith. a number of config shortcircuts are still available, for example it isnpossible to say `_pry_.input = StringIO.new` or `Pry.input = StringIO.new`. thenshortcuts are maintained for the Pry class and instances of the Pry class throughnPry::Config.shortcuts.nnPry::Config::Convenience adds a method called 'config_shortcuts' which can be usednto setup shortcut access to 'some_obj.config.blah' as 'some_obj.blah'nna lot of tests still fail, so work in progress.nnthis should help solve #1055.n

add Pry::LastException.pry adds behavior(methods) to the exception it returns at _pry_.last_exceptionnin a repl but when the exception has been passed along as a frozen object rubynwill raise an exception and pry fails to function as usual.nnthe commit changes that behavior so that the exception is wrapped in an instance ofnPry::LastException who is a subclass of BasicObject. Pry::LastException is a copy&pastenof what was defined dynamically in pry_instance.rb but it allows for frozen exceptionsnto remain frozen and still provides the methods pry dynamically defined on an exceptionnobject before. through a wrapper class pry also no longer modifies an exception objectnthat it doesn't own.n

Fix Pry.config.hooks # => parent's hooksPROBLEM DESCRIPTIONn===================nnThe child caches a dup of the parent's hooks,nso it does the correct thing after being accessed the first time.nnBut the first time it is called, it doesn't return its cached duped value,nit returns the parent's value. This causes 2 bugs:nn1. The first hook declared will get lost, because it is declaredn   to the parent hooks, not the child's hooks. And after that firstn   accessing, only the child's hooks will be usedn2. The parent's hooks (which are probably the ones fromn   [the default](https://github.com/pry/pry/blob/0ff6fa61d4197feace48b422b5e3d3fb5948cbdd/lib/pry/config/default.rb#L35-37))n   are going to get hooks declared on them that shouldn't ben   (well, presumably shouldn't be, given the explicit check forn   this case and duping to avoid it).n   So if another config object was initialized with the same parent,n   it would wind up with hooks that it didn't want/expect.nnI assume all the other keys work fine because they are value objects,nso if anything wanted to change the value, it would reassign the keynto the config object rather than mutating the returned value.nnMutability *sigh* yallknowwhatimsayinnnSOLUTION DESCRIPTIONn====================nnReturn the cached duped child value instead of the parent value.nnEXAMPLEn=======nnThis code fromn[the docs](https://github.com/pry/pry/blob/0ff6fa61d4197feace48b422b5e3d3fb5948cbdd/lib/pry/hooks.rb#L8-11)nwill not print hello, because it's being declared to the parent hook.nn```rubynPry.config.hooks.add_hook(:before_session, :say_hi) { puts hello }n```nnThis code will, b/c it's being declared to the cached, duped child hook.nn```rubynPry.config.hooksnPry.config.hooks.add_hook(:before_session, :say_hi) { puts hello }n```nnISSUE IMPACTn============nnFixes #1254nnMight fix or have something to do with these issues:nn* #1244 Totally thought I got it, but then couldn't reproduce again latern  and just don't understand how JRuby builds, so might just be a problemn  with how I was trying to reproduce it.n* #1171 Maybe, depending on if Eclipse integrates with it using then  hooks, alternatively, could be the same issue as the one above,n  they might both still be broken. Or both fixed and I can't figure outn  how to prove it. Dunno.nnOTHER THOUGHTSn==============nnI'm writing Github flavoured markdown,nbut I'm not actually sure if it will get rendered as such in the PR.nEsp since git considers leading octothorpes as comments and not headers,nand removes them...nnGuess we'll see... bottoms up, friends!n
Merge pull request #1271 from JoshCheek/fix_config_hooks_value_cachingFix Pry.config.hooks # => parent's hooks

Fix for RubiniusProblemn-------nnCurrently, CI is failing b/c singleton_class? was added to MRI2.1 but not Rbx.ne.g. https://travis-ci.org/pry/pry/builds/32133642nnHowever, I did not look into why it is suddenly failing now.nFor quite a while, Rbx builds were erroring out (e.g.  https://travis-ci.org/pry/pry/jobs/30421343)nThey are no longer failing, but are now erroring, for the above reason.nnContextn-------nnRbx has recently (11 days ago, 30 July 2014) received this methodnhttps://github.com/rubinius/rubinius/commit/2e71722dba53d1a92c54d5e3968d64d1042486fennBut the functionality has been available since April 2011nhttps://github.com/rubinius/rubinius/commit/4310f6b2ef3c8fc88135affe697db4e29e4621c4nnSolutionn--------nnFix the failures by falling back to the older functionality if we are on Rubinius,nand the new method is unavailable.n

Switch test suite to RSpecRemoves Bacon and MochannMostly this went smoothly. There were a few errors that I fixed alongnthe way, e.g. tests that were failing but for various reasons stillnpassed. Should have documented them, but didn't think about it untilnvery near the end. But generaly, I remember 2 reasons this would happen:n`lambda { raise omg }.should.raise(RuntimeError, /not-omg/)` will passnbecause the second argument is ignored by Bacon. And `1.should == 2`nwill return false instead of raising an error when it is not in an itnblock (e.g. if stuck in a describe block, that would just return false)nnThe only one that I felt unsure about was spec/helpers/table_spec.rbn`Pry::Helpers.tablify_or_one_line('head', %w(ing)).should == 'head: ing'`nThis is wrong, but was not failing because it was in a describe blockninstead of an it block.  In reality, it returns `head: ingn`,nI updated the test to reflect this, though I don't know for surenthis is the right thing to don

add Pry::Platform. (#1670)Platform is a category module that adds utility functions for queryingrnplatform information relating to Pry.rnrnSome methods are moved from BaseHelpers, and for backwards compatibilityrnincluded via 'include Pry::Platform'.rnrnmodule_function is not used by BaseHelpers anymore, in favour ofrninclude/extend being used in its place.rnrnThere is also less indentation noise in BaseHelpers module.rnWith _pry_.h (available on the backup master branch) these methodsrnexist on a single module that doesn't pollute the command scope, althoughrnfor backwards compatibility we still include the functions as top-levelrncommand functions.

add Pry::Testable, and friends. (#1679)* add Pry::Testable, and friends.rnrnThis commit replaces lib/pry/test/helper.rb by using category modules.rnThere's now:rnrn* Pry::Testable:rn  * Pry::Testable::Evalablern  * Pry::Testable::Mockablern  * Pry::Testable::Utilityrn  * Pry::Testable::PryTesterrnrn'include Pry::Testable' includes all of the above.rnFor the pry test suite it worked out best to include 'Pry::Testable' at the top-level.rnrnIn plugins I've written though this hasn't been the case, and I only normally need:rnPry::Testable::Evalable. So it reduces pollution for the third-party cases, which thisrncode is intended for since it lives within lib/ of the project.rnrnWhat do you think?rnrn* breaking change: add set_testenv_variables and unset_testenv_variablesrnrn* breaking change: add Pry::Testable::Variables, and renamernrnconstant_scope() to temporary_constants().rnrn* breaking change: rename inject_var as insert_variable, and move itsrnrndefinition to Pry::Testable::Variables.rnrn* include Pry::Testable::Evalable & include Pry::Testable::Variables intornrnthe top-level, but keep the other two modules spec-local.rnrn* document third argument of insert_variable.rnrn* update CHANGELOG.mdrnrn* note changelog entry is a breaking changernrn* update documentationrn

PluginManager#load_cli_options: use the realpath (#1762)* PluginManager#load_cli_options: use the realpathrnrnSince ruby 2.5, `require 'foo'` will use the realpath of the filerncorresponding to foo.rb. However `require '/absolute/path/to/foo.rb'`rnwon't use the realpath.rnrnSo when $GEM_HOME contains a symlink (ie it is not the realpath), when arnpry plugin is loaded, by `activate!`:rnrequire gem_name if !active?rnthe real_path of `gem_name` is used.rnrnBut then in load_cli_options:rncli_options_file = File.join(spec.full_gem_path, lib/#{spec.name}/cli.rb)rnrequire cli_options_file if File.exist?(cli_options_file)rnsince the path given is absolute, it will be used directly without realpath.rnrnThis means that cli.rb may potentially be required twice (once via its realpath if the plugin requires it, the other via its $GEM_HOME path when required by `load_cli_options`), which could raise some errors.rnrnFix this by using the realpath in load_cli_options too.rnrnRevision r59984 in ruby 2.5 introduced the use of realpath for load paths,rnand it was backported to version 2.4 in the minor revision 2.4.4. Sornonly use the realpath ourselves for ruby versions above or equal torn2.4.4.rn

core_extensions: make '__binding__' work with redefined #respond_to?Fixes https://github.com/pry/pry/issues/1596n(Unable to inspect object built from class)nReplaces https://github.com/pry/pry/pull/1719nBig thanks to @egwspiti for the repro case and the proposed PR.nnWhen a class redefines `respond_to?` or `method_missing` this leads to somenproblems and confuses Pry. I found another example where Pry misbehaves:nn```n[1] pry(main)> cd Class.new { def method_missing(*) end; def respond_to_missing?(*) true end; }.newnNoMethodError: private method `eval' called for nil:NilClassnfrom /Users/kyrylo/.gem/ruby/2.4.2/gems/pry-0.11.3/lib/pry/pry_instance.rb:163:in `inject_local'n```nnBy using `method_defined?` we can work around these bugs since this methodndoesn't check whether the receiver responds to a certain message but checksnwhether this method is defined (so we don't redefine it later). Seems like anwin-win.n

Rename HistoryArray to Ring`HistoryArray` is a very specific name and it doesn't tell the reader whatnit *really* means unless you read its code or the docs of the class.nnOn the other hand, `Ring` is a [very well-known term][1], which means exactlynwhat `HistoryArray` does. The alias name for it is circular buffer. I chosen`Ring` because it is shorter and used by Golang, so I expect programmers tonbe familiar with `Ring`.nn[1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circular_buffern

ring: rewrite the class to improve APICurrently, the Ring class is written with help of Hash as backend store.nAccording to the comments, the implementation should behave like a circularnbuffer, however it doesn't. Upon reaching maximum capacity Ring doesn't replacenold elements but keeps writing to new cells, deleting old cells, so that thenhash contains `nil` entries.nnThe new implementation is based on Array and seems to be closer to the actualnRing. Older elemens get overwritten with newer ones.nnThis class also includes Enumerable, however none of our APIs take advantage ofnit, so it seems like an overkill. There was also a problem with with this APInbecause of the above-mentioned nils. For example, if the ring exceeds itsnmaximum size, then callin `Enumerable#first` on it returns `nil`.nnThe new implementation deals with this with removal of Enumerable. The `#[]`nsyntax is preserved, and now `ring[0]` returns an actual element instead ofn`nil`. In case users need the Enumerable functionality, they can calln`Ring#to_a` to build the array, which supports the wanted methods.nnAs for the speed, the new implementation is:nn* slower overall because it's thread-safen* faster without mutexes for `#<<`n* slower without mutexes for `#[]`nnBenchmark for old implementation:nn```nWarming up --------------------------------------n Ring#<<   223.451k i/100msn Ring#[] 2.837k i/100msnCalculating -------------------------------------n Ring#<<223.157B (u00c2u00b1 3.4%) i/s -778.097Bn Ring#[] 82.485M (u00c2u00b1 9.4%) i/s -402.602M in   4.957792sn```nnBenchmark for this implementation:nn```nWarming up --------------------------------------n Ring#<<   211.587k i/100msn Ring#[] 1.974k i/100msnCalculating -------------------------------------n Ring#<<211.385B (u00c2u00b1 2.8%) i/s -698.439Bn Ring#[] 40.292M (u00c2u00b117.0%) i/s -190.069M in   4.971195sn```nnThe benchmark:nn```rbnrequire './lib/pry'nrequire 'benchmark/ips'nnBenchmark.ips do |x|n  empty_ring = Pry::Ring.new(100)n  populated_ring = Pry::Ring.new(100)n  150.times { |i| populated_ring << i }nn  x.report(Ring#<<) do |times|nempty_ring << timesn  endnn  x.report(Ring#[]) do |times|npopulated_ring[0]npopulated_ring[1]npopulated_ring[2]nnpopulated_ring[-1]npopulated_ring[-2]npopulated_ring[-3]nnpopulated_ring[1..2]npopulated_ring[-2..-1]npopulated_ring[-2..3]nnpopulated_ring[0..-1]nnpopulated_ring[2..-1]npopulated_ring[-1..10]nnpopulated_ring[-1..0]npopulated_ring[-1..1]n  endnendn```n

repl: correctly calculate overhang for empty linesThis improves on https://github.com/pry/pry/pull/1813.nnI spotted a problem with the way it works: sometimes, if you enter an emptynline, the output would span across two lines:nn```n[1] pry(main)>nn[2] pry(main)>nn[3] pry(main)>n```nnThis is because overhang is bigger than the current line. I also noticed a bugnwith method definition, where defining a method leaves an unwanted empty line:nn```n[3] pry(main)> def foon | endnn=> :foon```nnTo fix this I changed the way we calculate overhang. First and the mostnimportant change is that I stopped calculating overhang for emacs mode. This isnbecause it's too risky to introduce this change because it's the default modenand 99% of our users use this, so there's no need to change thisnbehaviour. Another reason is that emacs mode users typically don't use any modenindicators (because emacs has no modes), so it strikes me as a more pragmaticnsolution.nnWith Vi mode we calculate overhang and still support custom indicators.n
Merge pull request #1820 from pry/overhang-improvementrepl: correctly calculate overhang for empty lines

automatically call Pry::Config::Lazy objects before returning them.The pry-rails prompt uses `pry.config.prompt_name` but assumes itnwill always be a string and never tries to `.call` the object, which meansnwe can end up with a prompt like this:nn[2] [vagrant][development] #<Pry::Config::Lazy:0x000000000fde07b0>(main)>nnThis commit solves the problem for pry-rails and other prompts who makenthe same mistake by calling `.call` for them, automatically, upon read fromna config object.nnThe commit also removes the issue where every prompt has to deal with `prompt_name`nbeing a string / Proc-like object then acting accordingly.n

prevent LoadError being raised when using auto completions + Bundler. (#1896)* Prevent Bundler from raising a LoadError when accessing input completions.rnrnThe scenario:rnrn- $ mkdir foogemrn- $ cd foogemrn- $ echo source 'https://rubygems.org' > Gemfilern- $ bundle installrn- $ pry -rbundler/setuprn- type foo.<tab> into PryrnrnNotice that a LoadError is raised when trying to requirernpry/input_completer. This happens because Pry is not in thernGemfile, so once the sandbox is initialized by Bundler any requirernfor a Pry file is doomed to file.rnrnCouple that with the fact that '_pry_.config.completer' is notrnloaded until a user uses tab completion, and we end up with thisrnbroken situation.

Config#forget recursively removes a key from self and its default (#1899)The following example should return 'Readline' after 'input' has been forgotten:rn  # .pryrcrn  Pry.config.input = RbReadlinernrn   # Pry sessionrn   pry(main)> _pry_.config.forget(:input)rn   # This will unexpectedly return RbReadline instead of Pry's default, 'Readline'rn   pry(main)> _pry_.config.inputrn   => RbReadlinernrnThis commit fixes the above example to return 'Readline' after the 'input' option has been forgotten, allowing it to be restored to Pry's default.

history: inline #restore_default_behaviorThis method initialises variables and belongs to the `#initialize`nmethod. Apparently, this was needed for tests, but instead of restoringnbehaivour, we should be initializing a new objecty object, since encapsulationnis guaranteed us for free by Ruby.n

history: delete #pusher & #clearer, make the class Readline-agnostic1. The `options` parameter may contain the `:history` key, which contains an   history array (typically `Readline::HISTORY`)nn2. The `history` key is expected to have a history object as a value. Usually,n   it's `Readline::HISTORY`. This object *must* be Enumerable and implementn   `#clear` & `#to_a`. If nothing is provided, it defaults to an emptyn   array. As result, no hard dependency on `Readline` anymore.nn3. Removed duplicated history objects. It looks like the original code assumedn   that pushing to `Readline::HISTORY` also pushes to the file but it's not then   case. There doesn't seem to be a real need to keep two arrays of historyn

pry_instance: factor out command state to be globalThis change is aimed to simplify #1843 (Rework the Pry config).nnCurrent command state implementation gets in the way. We would like to simplifynthe Config class. The current implementation penetrates Pry codebase everywhere,nand during my rework of the config I discovered that `watch` uses global commandnstate.nnIt means the state should survive `Pry.new` calls. With my (unpublished yet)nimplementation, the `watch` command fails to do so. I realised that we cannrefactor command state implementation to be global. It makes sense to me andnalso helps with the Config refactoring.nnWith help of a dedicated class we can easily manage the commandnstate (resetting).n

Merge pull request #2021 from pry/config-influence-reductionReduce the influence of Pry::Config

Refactor ConfigFixes #1843 (Rework the Pry config)nnThere are a few breaking changes. They are mostly minor, so I decided not tonindroduce deprecations because it will considerable slow things down.nnKey changes:nn* `Pry.lazy` was replaced with `Pry::Configuration::LazyValue`nn  The config accepts three values now `LazyValue`, `MemoizedValue` and simplyn  `Value`. The main difference is that:n- `Value` is any value, including procs (so that an option returns a rawn  proc)n- `LazyValue` is a proc that is call on every invocation of an optionn- `MemoizedValue` is a value that is called only once (and then the optionn  always returns the return value of the )nn* `Pry.config.history` was a meta-option that held suboptions. However, the newn  config doesn't permit that (unless you know what you do)nn  Instead, we introduce a few options. For example:n- `Pry.config.history.histignore` becomes `Pry.config.history_ignorelist`n- `Pry.config.history.file` becomes `Pry.config.history_file`n- and so onnn  This was done so we can simplify configuration merging. Inlining option makesn  configuration implementation simpler, without losing much. The rule is thatn  you want to keep your options under your prefix (if you are an  plugin). Therefore, say, `Pry.config.pry_rescue.*` should ben  `Pry.config.pry_rescue_*` if you need merging.nnThe rest should behave in a similar fashion (and I rely heavily on our testnsuite to claim so).n
Merge pull request #2024 from pry/configuration-refactoringRefactor Config

history: cache @history.count to improve performanceFixes #2007 (Performance slowdown on entering lines)nnBy default, when we call `@history.count`, we actually calln`Readline::HISTORY.count`. It turns out this is a very expensive call (probablyn`O(n)`). My history file has over 50k lines and calling `count` makes thenproblem noticeable by spamming `Enter` as demostrated in the GIF in the issue.nnWe fix this issue by caching history line count and incrementing/resetting whennneeded.n
Merge pull request #2025 from pry/2007-performance-slowdown-fixhistory: cache @history.count to improve performance

commands/show_info: fix formatting error for C method headerFixes #2006 (show-source formatting bug in From)nnIn order to test this I had to build Pry from master locally and installnit. When I ran `String#initialize` I saw an error that `has_pry_doc` isnundefined on the Config class. This makes sense. This option is defined in thenpry-doc plugin.nnAs a workaround, I had to change the check to `defined?`. However, in thenfuture, we should make Pry plugin-agnostic - strictly no plugin checks in thencode.n
Merge pull request #2026 from pry/2006-show-source-formatting-fixcommands/show_info: fix formatting error for C method header

Merge Pry::Terminal with Pry::OutputFixes #1991 (Pry in a non-stdin/stdout PTY uses incorrect window size onnnon-JRuby platforms)nn`Pry::Terminal` was built without custom outputs in mind. We would always assumenthat `$stdout` is what the user wants. This contradicted the `output` confignoption.nnThanks to `Pry::Output`, which we use internally, we can decorate the outputnthat the user passes us with size methods. If we do that, we get improvednoutput support for free, so that PTY's `slave` can be passed to Pry and would benable to determine its size correctly (example from #1991).nnI do suspect that there are still some gotchas. Some commands or portions ofncode may still be assuming that `$stdout` is the only possible option. This hasnto be addressed separately, in the scope ofnhttps://github.com/pry/pry/issues/1988. The more tests we add, the easier itnwill be to uncover those spots.n
